segments.text: Full-time center managers, and they had their respective areas that they were out constantly seeing what we could do.
Need study, learn need study topics.
And then the divisions, so we wouldn't have any conflict with the divisions, they signed their staff to that center.
And those staff didn't report it to any manager.
The center manager had no administrative control over any of the people.
Provided need studies, lots of good, and we had those available.
When we started to offer the agency, the independent drillers came.
So I said, well, here's what you're going to take.
And I said, give us the, they underwrote the program.
We believe you don't have anything.
Looking back on those 19 years, is there any area of service, and I don't mean geographic area, but any topic,
that you wish you all could have done more?
Were you frustrated that you couldn't have served this or this or this industry?
See, the Engineering Containment Service is the only agency in the state of Texas.
They have a statewide mandate.
And normally in all those cases, there's some trade association or something.
What were your favorite groups to work with?
There must have been some that were more pleasant than others, though.
Who were the key state officials?
I don't know if you can name your favorites.
The ones that you would say thank you to.
I guess the one, Joe Reynolds.
See, Joe Reynolds and White was in the law practice.
And White was his new mate.
He was the Secretary of State, because I knew White when he was on the run for governor.
I felt that he's the only governor I really, really knew.
You know, for any, I've known all the governors, but I mean, you really know them.
So I guess that's one reason I felt it close to him.
You know, Preston helped me out an awful lot.
Anytime I wanted to form him with any senator or representative, I could call him Bill, he'd hand it for me.
This was while he was...
State Chairman, was he, well, while he was a representative, and as he served, you know, he served his term as the state of Texas.
The House Appropriation Committee for about 10 or 12 years.
Whenever I wanted to form him with any senator or House of Representatives, I'd call him Bill, and he'd hand it for me.
Of course, Bill Moore, he was in the Senate.
I'd done a lot of other work for Bill Moore on his outside, and he had that back of A&M on him for charge, and that back of A&M was Bill, and he helped everybody out with that.
Can you, can you give me an example of...
lobbying at work, where you called somebody and they made the wheels turn?
Give, take, describe.
For a specific project?
If you, if there was one.
You can think of them.
Yeah, a bunch of volunteer fire departments.
It takes them to tie in with Harris County.
It's a very expensive training program.
You've got to have good training to be damn careful.
And I said, it's true, the fuel's expensive, and you've got to burn.
You can't just light a match and say, here, now we're gonna go put it out.
I said, you've got to, if you're gonna have any fire training or those types of training, you've got to have hands-on training.
They've got to smell the heat and see what's going on.
But anyway, so, the way I stopped it, I went down to the organizer.
What do you want?
Give me an opportunity to say no.
So finally, what there'd be a big gripe was, there's a volunteer fire department, and they didn't have anybody to place the train on site.
They'd open the damn fire key on Saturday morning.
And that was their big gripe.
You know, they worked five days a week, and they didn't have any place to come on in.
It was too expensive.
They didn't have any lights and so forth.
What time do you want it?
You want to open it at ten on Saturday?
Burn it till six.
They would kill that one.
But another, at the same time, they were trying to get one out the rest of the time.
And the word got to them then what we did.
But then they used the excuse that we live too far away.
We can't come that distance.
Alright, can you give an example of where you needed some help in the legislature?
You needed to get a bill passed or some funding,
and give me an example of where some people stepped up
to help the extension service.
No, I'll request for state appropriated money.
The only state appropriated money, the way I used my state appropriated money
was for the volunteer fire departments and the growing million dollars.
They didn't support our programs.
I presented my bill, but I had programs that we had a $39 million.
We didn't have any in-house fights with the board or other agencies.
In fact, I had, on numerous occasions, extension service
to get their money the way I got mine.
And John Dutch said one time, the chancellor of the system,
I guess he was about to answer that,
by the way, he had them all, and his main complaint was
he had a different clientele.
You know, my comeback would tell me a poor group of volunteers.
Alright, now, you reported to Benson and Calhoun
under Dr. Williams when you were first.
Alright, Dr. Williams has the heart attack,
and then the system is recreated,
the chancellor of the system recreated
in 76, and Jarvis Miller becomes president.
Now, Ludeke went in and served for Williams.
Right, right.
And tell them about working with General Ludeke.
I said, yes, sir, and I knew it, but I didn't argue with him.
How long did it take him to make up his mind about something?
Well, when they told me I was going to move,
that they were going to move the headquarters,
my friend told me, now, this is temporary.
And Dr. Williams told me, they've all agreed with me
that we have this eyesore for the university.
Now, this is from that, down at the south.
So, Ludeke was in the community.
When I went down there to see them,
they had my reproduction shop.
I always had my own reproduction shop.
I admit, it was probably the only one.
Industrial economics, I had my own reproduction facility.
So, I could control the time.
I could move my projects around any way I wanted to.
So, I had to deliver them.
But I had a reproduction shop from day one.
And a lot of people made it.
Now, this was for printing?
Yeah.
Materials?
Yes.
Artistic work?
Yeah.
Because all of mine was sponsored research.
And, you know, when I brought down there,
and I had Exxon, I had contracts for Exxon
for seven or eight straight years.
And you made it to their board.
Well, they expected a First Quest presentation.
They didn't want to see some carbon paper stuck out.
That was quality.
And that was built into the price.
But anyway, when I went down to see them,
there was stuff coming up and down.
Of course, I'd gone into really, you know,
developing good lesson plans, good technical management.
And we had part of a reproduction shop still do that.
They built that building out.
And by the way, you know, we even paid for our building.
We built that $250,000 building out at the annex.
We built that $500,000 Fred Benson up.
He put $500,000 into it.
We built that bomb building.
We built that.
Hazardous materials.
I built that out of my feed, you know.
I asked them whether it was right or wrong.
I operated the engineering facility.
I did the extension services.
I charged for everything.
There was no free things.
I mean, it was all built into the price.
So, we were able to do this kind of thing.
But anyway, we got that.
So, Jim and Luke, he said,
Well, I don't know the thing about reproduction.
I said, Well, let's put it down on the first floor
so people can get in and get out.
And we moved that down.
Well, that caused...
Who had that before?
Who had that?
Whoever had that shop was going to do it.
People were going to do it.
And Jim and Luke got on the phone and said,
Make those things.
Right from his office.
Who was that guy that had that?
I don't remember.
All right.
Then when General Ludeke steps aside,
then, let's see, Jarvis is president
and Dr. Williams is here for another couple of years.
How did your reporting process change then?
To whom did you report?
Well, they made Pinson vice president.
But now, you know, I'd give them a continuing education
after five years.
You know, I only took that job for five years.
I was out of continuing education.
And that fifth year come up just about the time Jarvis took over.
Right.
So, you then, by and large, reported to the system,
not through the president's office.
Well, I can't say that because I had to make
a budget presentation one year ago.
Okay.
All right.
So, what was the first meeting of his key people?
Did you meet with them?
All right.
Did...
No, the agencies did.
All right.
Did Dr. Williams, did he, when he gathered the agencies,
you met with them when he was chancellor?
Well, one or two meetings we had, yes.
All right.
Then when he left, Frank Hubert became the chancellor.
What, did the routine change at all?
The first thing, he told me the first thing he liked,
I mean, Fred and Dean Hubert.
All right.
Then take me on up through the 80s.
Were there any changes in the routine with different presidents
and different chancellors?
Well, of course, Richardson took over.
Wait, we skipped the man from Purdue.
No, Hanson.
Hanson.
He was chancellor.
Well, it was about 84.
Oh, and Richardson became dean of engineering?
Oh, I'm sorry.
Yeah.
Yeah.
He became dean of engineering.
All right.
He was also...
Describe his management style.
Comment.
Was it...
It was less direct than Benson and Calhoun had been.
Herb never...
I can't say enough because Herb objected to a thing I wanted to do.
He proved everything.
I sat down and I met with him once a month.
Where Herb's problems was caused by his dad, Jack Flipsey.
And we only had one conflict.
Now, you've got to realize I'm a very organized person.
I believe in an organizational chart.
I believe it and I follow it.
But anyway, you want me to put this on tape?
Let me cut it off.
Let me just talk a little bit.
As you look back, you served 19 years under a number of different presidents and chancellors.
I'm not going to ask the negative, but in the positive, to which ones would you give
the highest, as many as you want to, which ones deserve the highest credit?
During that 19-year period?
Of course.
I'd have to say Dr. Liggett was in place number one.
I'd have to say Dr. Liggett was in place number two.
I'd have to say Dr. Liggett was in place number three.
I'd have to say Dr. Liggett was in place number four.
I'd have to say Dr. Liggett was in place number five.
I'd have to say Dr. Liggett was in place number six.
You got to do this on the video.
And then, the next question we have is, we're not going to ask the negative, but in the
positive, to which ones would you give the highest, as many as you want to, which ones
deserve the highest credit?
During that 19-year period?
Of course.
I'd have to say Dr. Liggett was in place number one.
Why?
Well, I just think he was more knowledgeable about the types of programs that the engineering
detention centers were using.
I think that he accepted them on their merit, not in his second class.
He never did give me the truant of giving them the truant, but he says that that's
what the time period for me, I need to before the recording, is.
So here's what I'm going to say about this.
He was very easy to talk to.
Who else?
Well, of course, Mr. Benson.
I'm taking him from the top down now.
Mr. Benson and I had such a long-term relationship with each other.
We had it from about 55 to 54, whenever he became a team.
Until he got Tony retired, we had a good relationship after he retired.
Fred was always to the point, which I like.
Fred had a lot of character.
He'd always, if you were going to go out of town with him, you'd say you'd pick him up
He'd stand around on the porch waiting for you at 730.
He'd always ask you if you were going to go to a meeting where there was going to be
a legislative meeting, like, Jim, is there anything you want me to say?
He'd always ask me that question.
Is there an area you want me to comment on?
And I always said no, because I couldn't get to tell you.
I think Fred was a very smart guy.
He was a very good guy.
He was a very good guy.
He was a very good guy.
He was a very good guy.
He was a very good guy.
He was a very good guy.
He was a very good guy.
He was a very good guy.
And I always said no, because I couldn't get to tell you.
I think Fred was a very smart individual.
He certainly commanded the attention of a lot of people when he spoke.
A lot of people listened.
And I admired that in him.
So, I'd have to put him on top, and then the next man was Calhoun.
I was told to talk to Calhoun.
He had a lot of good ideas.
Where did he go?
working in relationships together.
In my opinion, I'm not saying one was better than the other, but in my opinion, we had a completely different type of leadership after the middle 80s.
It was completely different.
Did it become more bureaucratic?
Yes, it was strictly bureaucratic.
You didn't feel at ease, you didn't feel at ease picking up the phone and calling.
I never did it in the first place, but I always knew that I could if I wanted to talk to Dr. Calhoun.
I didn't have to worry about Dr. Williams or Calhoun chewing me out for calling Dr. Williams or vice versa.
Mr. Benson, I mean, I didn't ever do it to my knowledge, but I always felt comfortable in doing such a thing like that.
We were more, in my opinion, we were more professional.
We respected each other more.
We had a great deal of respect for each other, and I think that was probably the warning greetings.
It made those change in us, taking forward to the time I retired in 92.
We had a closeness, I think.
I felt to him as my friend, and not only as my boss, but my friend.
Now, other than your senior partners, whom did you turn to for advice and counsel and input most often?
To my committees.
To my committees.
We had advisory committees in every sector of my Engineering Detention Service program, made up of the leaders in their field.
Like the telephone association, I'd have top telephone members.
Power company, I'd have somebody from the power company.
And we had advisory committees.
We had one whole law advisory committee for the Engineering Detention Service.
We had one meeting a year, and I'd call it in various parts of the state.
But other committee members would, you know, just pick up the phone and ask.
I kept them informed.
If it was on my telephone committee, you got it.
And I didn't delude them or anything, but the things they ought to see, I sent it to them.
That's who I got help from, my users.
As you look back, can you think of any decisions you wish that Texas A&M had made that it didn't make?
I think they should have gone for co-education.
I can't say that because I don't have the background.
All right.
Let's talk about that a minute.
Co-education, higher admission requirements, racial integration,
broadening the curriculum, non-compulsory core, all those came in the 60s.
Did those affect your effort?
No.
You'd be surprised, I always traveled with an internship, and you'd be surprised at the number.
I never took a trip that I didn't.
The only one that's hurting it is people who don't.
Now, you rode to Austin for a number of years to reserve meetings with Earl Rudder.
Well, yes.
And I always assigned a driver out of my unit to drive for him.
Oh.
And when I quit that, it's because the last three that I assigned as drivers, they got them in Westport.
Oh, I see.
I see.
But I only filled in there for a period of about...
So, all right.
During those years that you and Mr.
Rudder were going to the same meeting then in Austin,
describe your relationship with him and the reserve.
For one time, I let myself down.
You were going to his meeting on Monday night.
You know, he'd have to be back.
We'd be back by Mr.
Rudder.
Mr.
Rudder nominated me on the way back to Atlanta.
He had the ability to do that.
He said, well, what did y'all discuss?
Well, we discussed the military, quite a bit.
We discussed military personnel, quite a bit.
The university, the only thing that would come up about the university, you know,
he'd ask you some questions that you really had no answer.
And you'd say, well, let's just say I don't think he ever asked this question.
He'd just say, these are the type of questions he'd ask.
Well, has... Well, has making the Corps adoptive of the persons coming to the university,
has that had any effect on you?
You know, I'd say, me personally?
He'd say, well, personally, not a lot.
I'd say, no.
We're living in a different world.
You know, I said, I wouldn't take all the money in the world for my years I spent in the Corps of Cadets.
I said, but that was in 1940.
And I said, I've got two sons.
And I said, they're both in the Corps.
But I guarantee you, I didn't push them into the Corps.
They went there on their own.
There you go.
But we never did get into personalities.
We never did with me because, as I say, I was two ranks below him.
I didn't have any relationship with him as him being my boss other than in the military.
Can you share any anecdotes or amusing or interesting things that happened going to or from that involved Mr. Rutter?
No, but did anything ever go wrong?
Did you all ever have a flat or get there late or anything like that?
Well, I got stopped several times for speeding.
Oh, really?
Oh, yeah.
And what would the highway patrol say?
Give us a ticket.
Oh, he gave you.
It didn't matter whose car that was?
We were driving a military vehicle.
Mr. Rutter liked to get where he was going fast.
I don't know if anybody's ever told you that before.
No, I didn't know that.
Well, he wasn't allergic to pushing the metal to the pedal.
I don't know how many tickets he got, but with me, I don't know.
All right, who paid the tickets?
Okay, so you don't know.
I don't know.
You don't know.
Okay.
I never did ask him.
He always would take the ticket from me.
All right.
He took the one ticket from me.
All right.
When the highway patrol would stop, did it impress the highway patrol that here was a major general?
Well, that only happened one time with me.
Oh, okay.
And I doubt if that highway patrol knew a major general.
All right, so he didn't even talk to the person in the back seat.
Okay.
I'm just talking about one time.
It was late at night.
Mr. Rutter had a sense of humor?
Can you give me any examples?
I told you, I had an infantry battalion.
I picked out a beautiful, I had a nice row of trees, and we'd come right, so I said,
okay, we're going to come right down to our tanks.
Mr. Rutter makes the other general go up.
I went up to this gentleman.
I said, now, there's a lot of wood rattlers here.
And I said, in fact, I said, there's one right by your foot.
He's a little bit sharp there.
Put your boots on.
They won't bother you.
But anyway, we went up to this thing.
By that time, boy, everything was going to be different.
I mean, I had an infantry battalion.
I had an infantry battalion.
I had an infantry battalion.
I had an infantry battalion.
I had an infantry battalion.
I had an infantry battalion.
I had an infantry battalion.
I had an infantry battalion.
They were all down there.
I always had the time to write to America.
Zoom!
Zoom!
Zoom!
And I had a little awful time with them.
So, Mr. Rutter had to go up and I was there.
I told this gentleman, I said, sir, I said, there's another rattler that went crazy about
your foot.
And I just put my foot back there and stopped playing.
He said, get him back.
You did it.
So I got into his car and said, now, are you sure that rattler thing didn't matter?
I said, I'll show you.
He said, I'd like to see you at one o'clock today, tomorrow.
And I thought he was going to get me for telling him about the damn rattler thing.
He said, what, damn it, Curl?
He said, when I said, made it realistic, he said, I didn't want you to run over us.
I said, well, I said, at that slope, I said, you know, I said, to make it realistic, we had to come take part of that slope.
He said, I didn't want that there, Curl.
As far as you know, when Earl Rudder was president of A&M, to whom did he turn for advice most often?
To whom, whose advice did he listen to most carefully?
In-house?
Mm-hmm.
All right.
Then you?
It might surprise you, though, if you didn't know.
It might be some instructor down there or something.
You said in-house.
All right, let's go out of the house.
Away from the campus, whose advice did he hear most?
Well, he had ear to the board's advice.
He had a lot of respect for the board.
Which, who were the key board members during his day?
Oh, in 70.
In 69.
Sterling Evans, Zachary.
Clyde Wells.
Clyde Wells was on it, and Mrs. Wilson from Lubbock was on it.
